TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Dynamic Model of Organizational Decision Making: Chemco Revisited Six Years After Bhopal
AU  - Kunreuther, Howard
AU  - Bowman, Edward H.
Y1  - 1997/08/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.8.4.404
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.8.4.404
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 404
EP  - 413
VL  - 8
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The authors develop a dynamic model of organization decision making that is motivated by the decision-making process at a multinational chemical firm, given the pseudonym Chemco, that they visited shortly after the Union Carbide explosion in Bhopal, India, and again six years later. Two major decisions were taken by Chemco that could be attributed in large part to the Bhopal disaster: the divestiture of one of its plants and the sale of a business. An analysis of those actions by Chemco underscores the importance of reference points and constraints in influencing organizational choices.
